    <h1>Designing the Swagger Definition Objects</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <div class=3D"sectionColumnWrapper">
<div class=3D"sectionMacro">
<div class=3D"sectionMacroRow">
<div class=3D"columnMacro">
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"relative-table wrapped confluenceTable" style=3D"width: 26.=
34%;">
<colgroup>
<col style=3D"width: 46.04%;">
<col style=3D"width: 53.93%;">
</colgroup>
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Page Status</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<div class=3D"content-wrapper">
<p><span class=3D"status-macro aui-lozenge aui-lozenge-moved">TO BE REVIEWE=
D</span></p>
</div></th>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<h2 id=3D"DesigningtheSwaggerDefinitionObjects-SwaggerDefinitions"><strong>=
Swagger Definitions<br></strong></h2>
<p>The swagger definitions can be classified into 3 types:</p>
<ol>
<li>Common Data Types</li>
<li>API Entity Model</li>
<li>Request or Response</li>
</ol>
<h3 style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;" id=3D"DesigningtheSwaggerDefinitionObjec=
ts-CommonDataTypes"><strong>Common Data Types</strong></h3>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">There are Westpac Mesh<span style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(0,0,0);">&nbsp;A</span>PI resources that are common throughout most =
if not all APIs. This will contain the main Error definition, but can also =
contain other common definitions in the future.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Examples include: Currency amount, balanc=
es, percentage representation, identifiers. Please refer to the <a href=3D"=
/display/MESH/Common+Data+Types">Common Data Types</a> page for more inform=
ation.</p>
<h3 style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;" id=3D"DesigningtheSwaggerDefinitionObjec=
ts-APIEntityModel"><strong>API Entity Model</strong></h3>
<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong>There is a d=
efinition section in the swagger Spec that contains reusable definitions.<s=
trong> <br></strong></p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">These definitions represent the core mode=
l of the API and contain only the properties that could be used within the =
scope of the resources defined for the API. For example, the customer resou=
rce for an API designed to expose only contact information would only defin=
e the email, telephone and/or postal addresses of the customer along with c=
ustomer identifiers. It would not contain the IDV status and other demograp=
hic properties as they are not in the scope of the API.</p>
<h3 style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;" id=3D"DesigningtheSwaggerDefinitionObjec=
ts-RequestandResponseDefinitions"><strong style=3D"font-size: 16.0px;">Requ=
est and Response Definitions</strong></h3>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">These definitions describe the objects an=
d parameters that are part of each resource's request and response. Request=
 definitions include header parameters, query parameters, path parameters a=
nd body elements. Response definitions include header parameters (if applic=
able), body elements and HTTP response codes.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">The body elements will contain the defini=
tions from the API entity model.</p>
<p style=3D"margin-left: 30.0px;">Examples include: Search customer, which =
is implemented as a POST operation, and thus the request has a body contain=
ing the search criteria.</p>
<p><br></p>
<h2 id=3D"DesigningtheSwaggerDefinitionObjects-Generalmodeldesign">General =
model design</h2>
<ul>
<li>Consistently use the same name for fields which are exposed as both req=
uest and response elements</li>
<li>Ensure consistency with names from other API's within the domain and/or=
 sub-domain</li>
<li>Nest foreign key relations as this allows simple&nbsp; future inlining =
of extra information, e.g. { customer: { id: 1234} } not { customerId: 1234=
 }</li>
<li><p>A flat structure is preferred over a deeply nested structure in requ=
est body or responses.&nbsp; If there are more than three levels in the JSO=
N data structures you may be exposing too much information in a single reso=
urce - this does not mean keep everything flat, provide structure were appr=
opriate.within their associated entities. I.e. don't have customer identifi=
er information and arrangement identifier information at the root level, ha=
ve a separate customer and arrangement that contain their identifiers</p><p=
>{ customer: { id: 1234}, arrangement:{ id: 0987} } not { customerId: 1234,=
 arrangementId: 0987 }</p></li>
</ul>
<h2 id=3D"DesigningtheSwaggerDefinitionObjects-Requestmodeldesign">Request =
model design</h2>
<ul>
<li>Expose only the minimal number of parameters to consumers which are req=
uired for processing within the API.&nbsp; If an API can derive a field for=
 processing then don't ask the consumer to provide it.</li>
</ul>
<h2 id=3D"DesigningtheSwaggerDefinitionObjects-Responsemodeldesign">Respons=
e model design</h2>
<ul>
<li>Don't echo information in the payload which was provided in the request=
 - if a consumer knows the customerId in the request, they should not need =
it in the response</li>
<li>If the response model (ignoring paging a collection) is more than a pag=
e of text when printed out, then&nbsp;you may be exposing too much informat=
ion in a single resource</li>
<li>Don't send fields with null data&nbsp;- just don't&nbsp;send&nbsp;them<=
/li>
<li>The response model should be encapsulated within a root object named 'd=
ata'</li>
<li>Use the appropriate HTTP response code based on the semantics of the op=
eration and the outcome of processing within the API (ie. success or failur=
e).&nbsp; Use 2xx codes for successful processing, 4xx for failed processin=
g due to invalid data supplied by the caller, 5xx for failed processing due=
 to server error</li>
<li>For error scenarios, expose the standard error structures. Map only bus=
iness important provider errors.</li>
<li>Include pagination information, where appropriate, within a root object=
 named 'paging'</li>
</ul>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl hide-border-bottom" style=3D"borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px;">
